s with authorization2star  aChristian Democracy swept across parts of Latin America, gaining influence in Venezuela in the 1940s, Chile in the 1950s, El Salvador and Guatemala in the 1960s, and Costa Rica and Mexico in the 1980s. This book offers an overview of Christian Democracy in the region— underscoring its remarkable diversity—and examines the Christian Democratic organizations of Chile and Mexico, which are still major parties today. The concluding section analyzes the demise of formerly significant Christian Democratic parties in El Salvador, Guatemala, Peru, and Venezuela. Christian Democracy in Latin America provides the definitive stufy of the nature, rise, and decline of Christian Democracy in Latin America. The book enriches the broader theoretical literature on political parties by highlighting the distinctive strategic dilemmas parties face, and the distinctive objectives they pursue, in contexts of fragile democracy or of authoritarian regimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh1 aCrisp, Brian F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Kirk A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuneeus, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Daniel H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoaeza, Soledad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagaloni, Beatriz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMainwaring, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMainwaring, Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMolina, José E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt, Gregory D., e